data.content:
Three distinct C# 13 breaking changes. Here's what breaks and the fixes:

### 1. `Buffer.cs` — `[InlineArray]` banned on `record struct`
C# 13 disallows `[InlineArray]` on record structs (the compiler-synthesized equality/`ToString` can't work correctly on inline arrays). Fix: use a plain `struct`:

```csharp
[System.Runtime.CompilerServices.InlineArray(10)]
struct Buffer
{
    private int _element0;
}
```

### 2. `Generator.cs` — `stackalloc` in local function inside iterator
C# 13 extended ref-safety analysis into local functions within iterators/async methods (they're now part of the state machine context). `stackalloc` in a local function inside an iterator is no longer allowed. Fix: extract to a separate static method:

```csharp
unsafe class DataGenerator
{
    IEnumerable<int> Generate()
    {
        yield return 1;
        Process();
    }

    static void Process()
    {
        int* p = stackalloc int[10];
        // ... work with pointer
    }
}
```

### 3. `Resolver.cs` — Collection expression `[]` now ambiguous
C# 13 broadened collection expression conversions so both `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>` are equally valid targets. `Process([])` is now ambiguous between the two overloads. Fix: add an explicit cast:

```csharp
static void Main()
{
    Process((ReadOnlySpan<int>)[]);
}
```
